item.title: NARROW GAUGE STATION (OO-9)
item.description:
NARROW GAUGE STATION


PLEASE READ MY PROFILE BEFORE DOWNLOADING


This is a re-work of a previous building. It is intended to be a narrow gauge station in !:76 scale. I hope I've got it right. The design comes from my imagination and is not authentic in any way. I hope I've got the scale about right.


There is a version with a partial platform canopy but I have not test printed it yet.


DIMENSIONS
L 173mm (excluding steps)
D 111mm (excluding steps)
H 82mm

Doors are about 26mm tall.

A REQUEST
I spend a lot of time designing and testing. Please do not download and print my designs for sale.

FEEDBACK
I produce these designs for my own use and share for free. I sincerely hope this design prints well for you. If you get a good print, please post a photo or two. If you have any issues with the design, please feedback politely in the comments and I will do my best to fix. I can also carry out requested modifications or re-scales if they are possible.

PRINTING
Please refer to the print settings below.

item.title: Kirby Portable Fume Extractor
item.description:
This fume extractor is remixed to add a cavity for a 18650 3.7V Li-Ion Cell and USB charging circuitry gutted from a portable charger. I put a switch between the 5V power and the 5V DC 80mm x 80mm fan from amazon. It also has a 4.7 x 4.7 x 0.3in Carbon Filter that I had to cut to fit in front of the 80mm fan.

It can be charged with a micro-usb cable just like any cheap portable low-amp USB charger from the convenience store (not a large powerbank).

I soldered the fan power (5 VDC) wire to the switch and then the switch to 5V pin on the USB connecter trace. There's enough space in the extractor TOP model for the wiring from the battery to the USB charging circuit and the wiring to/from the switch.

5V DC 80mm x 80mm fan:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B019ORFSD8/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_search_asin_title?ie=UTF8&psc=1

item.title: Glowing Halloween Tombstone Keychain
item.description:
One idea that came to my head was a design related to the dead.

Only 45 minutes to make, it takes no longer than cookies to bake.

Familiar with the wear and tear of a key fob, I thought a 100% infill may do the job.

Drawn in Krita and made in Blender, then taken to Cura to render.

If you have read this far, I reward you a gold star.

If you have enjoyed this post in some way, throw a like my way.

If you have printed the file, then post your makes which I check for during my breaks.

Thank you for taking the time to read these silly rhymes.

Now I'm off to plan more designs.

item.title: Laser engraving and cutting test files
item.description:
Using new materials to cut or engrave with your laser cutter/engraver needs some testing before the actual 'work'.

Several test files are online. A lot of them take many time to get ready, especially when cutting is tested because some materials/thicknesses need multiple passes. So I made a simple set of gcode files to make life easier.

A test needs just 10cm by 10cm

Step 1. Just for positioning. It draws a 10cm by 10cm box with the laser at 1%. This step could be skipped since you probably have a laser which can also draw a frame to do the same.

Step 2: engraving the labels on top and on the side.

Step 3a is for test cutting, 3b is for test engraving.
Engraving will just run once, engraving 25 boxes of 1cm by 1cm in a 5 by 5 grid
Cutting will run up to 10 passes. Before each pass it will put a little I in the box with the word passes on top. Each pass it will add one I. After 4 passes, the line for the fifth pass wil go diagonally through the previous 4 lines. Then it starts with another set blow the first set of lines.
After 1 full pass the laser will return home and pause 10 seconds so you have some time to stop the laser if the desired number of passes has been reached (full cut through the material for instance)

Both cutting and engraving will start bottom left. First engraving/cutting at low power and high speed. Each new box will be first at a lower speed, then higher power. So power will increase while speed decreases. My engraving example (see photo) I should have stopped my laser engraver a little sooner before the last (way to heavy engraved) box was drawn.

Step 4 is cutting the box around the test. Depending on the material you have to run this multiple times.
